  "statement": {
    "en": "Tumor-promoting roles of the chromatin-associated DEK oncogene in metastatic melanoma",
    "ja": null,
    "latex": null,
    "preview_source": "tier7-ingest-v0.2",
    "summary": "As a multifunctional, conserved yet unique non-histone chromatin-architectural factor, the DEK oncoprotein is known to be involved in multiple nuclear processes, including chromatin remodeling, transcriptional regulation, and DNA damage response. Although aberrant DEK expression has been identified in various cancers, its precise mechanistic contribution to tumorigenesis remains incompletely understood. This includes its genome-wide chromatin binding patterns in cancer cells and how this affects chromatin structure and cellular functions. Therefore, the aim of this thesis is to investigate the chromatin binding landscape and functional role of DEK in chromatin organization and transcriptional regulation with a particular focus on phosphorylation-dependent modulation by the casein kinase 2 "
  },
